      <header class="pg-header">
        <p class="pg-eyebrow">Saturday</p>
        <h1 class="pg-title">Saturn</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Roman god of time, agriculture, and the underworld — named in Scripture as Remphan</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        Every Saturday on the Gregorian calendar honors a Roman god whose worship was ancient before Rome itself was founded. His name was <strong>Saturn</strong> (Greek <em>Kronos</em>, Babylonian <em>Kaiwan</em>, biblical <em>Remphan</em>). He was the god of time, of agriculture, and of the dead. His worship is one of the oldest and darkest in the pagan world — and he is one of the few false gods named explicitly in Scripture as a name Yahuah's people once bore in idolatry.
      </p>

      <h2>Who He Was</h2>

      <p>
        Saturn was the Roman name for the god the Greeks called Kronos — the father of Jupiter, the ruler of the golden age, the lord of time itself. He was associated with the harvest (the sickle was his symbol), with the passage of time, and with the dead. The Romans dedicated the seventh day of the week to him — <em>dies Saturni</em>, Saturn's day. Of all seven Roman planetary day-names, this one passed unchanged into English: Old English <em>Sæterndæg</em>, becoming Saturday.
      </p>

      <p>
        But Saturn's worship goes back further than Rome. The same god was worshiped under different names across the ancient Near East — Kaiwan in Babylon, Chiun in early Hebrew sources, and most importantly <strong>Remphan</strong> in the Greek translation of Amos and in the New Testament. Stephen, in his speech before he was martyred, named this idol directly:
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Acts 7:42–43</span> — "…as it is written in the book of the prophets, O ye house of Israel, have ye offered to me slain beasts and sacrifices by the space of forty years in the wilderness? Yea, ye took up the tabernacle of Moloch, and the star of your god Remphan, figures which ye made to worship them…"
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Amos 5:26</span> — "But ye have borne the tabernacle of your Moloch and Chiun your images, the star of your god, which ye made to yourselves."
      </div>

      <p>
        Israel carried the worship of Saturn (Remphan, Chiun, Kaiwan) with them out of Egypt. Yahuah saw it. He named it. And He sent them into exile partly because they would not put it down. The "star of your god Remphan" is the symbol that has come down to us as the six-pointed star — a symbol associated with Saturn-worship in the ancient world long before it was associated with anything else.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        Of all the day-names on the Roman calendar, Saturn is the one Scripture names directly as an idol Yahuah's own people fell into. This is not obscure pagan history. This is biblical history. Saturn-worship is named in Amos. It is named in Acts. The day at the end of the Roman week carries the name of the very god Yahuah sent Israel into exile for following.
      </p>

      <p>
        There is also another layer. Many in the Torah-keeping world teach that "Saturday is the Sabbath" — and the well-meaning instinct behind that teaching is right (the Sabbath is real, the Sabbath is commanded), but the conclusion mixes Babylon's clock with Yahuah's clock. Yahuah did not name His Sabbath after Saturn. He sanctified the seventh day at creation, long before any Roman week existed and long before any pagan god received a day in his honor.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Some will ask: <em>"Then what about the Sabbath? Isn't Saturday the Sabbath?"</em> This is exactly the kind of mixing the calendar studies on this site keep pointing to.
      </p>

      <p>
        Saturday is a Roman day named after a Roman god — Saturn, Remphan, the very idol Yahuah sent His people into exile for bearing. It belongs to Babylon's clock — the continuous seven-day rotation tied to pagan deities. Yahuah's clock does not have a Saturday. Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He hung in the heavens. The new moon is Day 1 of the month — a non-work day, though not a Sabbath. From there the days are numbered, and <strong>the Sabbaths fall on Days 8, 15, 22, and 29</strong>. When the next new moon appears, the count resets.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>There is no Saturday in this system.</strong> The Sabbath of Yahuah is counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from a continuous rotation that lined itself up with Saturn. To say "the Sabbath is Saturday" is to commit the same error as "Christ died on a Friday." It mixes two clocks that were never meant to translate into each other. The Sabbath is real. The Sabbath is commanded. But the Sabbath is not anchored to a Roman day named after Remphan.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        Knowing where the name "Saturday" came from is not optional history. Scripture itself names Remphan. Stephen names him in Acts 7. Amos named him centuries before. The very god whose worship cost Israel her freedom is the god whose name closes the Roman week. To say "I keep Saturday as the Sabbath" is to unintentionally name Remphan as the marker of Yahuah's holy day.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them when the Sabbath has come. The world watches its phone and lets Saturn tell it what day it is. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        Saturday is Saturn's day. Saturn is Remphan. Yahuah's Sabbath is counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from a Roman day named after the idol He sent His people into exile for bearing.
      </div>

